<DOC><DOCNO> AP890904-0118 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-04-89 1916EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-04 0424</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0442</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms Drench The Nation's Midsection</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A broad area of thunderstorms soaked the central Plains withheavy rains on Labor Day, but most of the western half of the nationhad sunny skies and eastern skies were clear to partly cloudy.   The rain fell heaviest across eastern Nebraska, eastern Kansas,western Iowa, and northern and western Missouri, with most placesgetting about 2 inches, with between 3 and 5 inches reported in someareas.   Flood warnings issued for eastern Nebraska's Maple Creek in DodgeCounty, which swelled to 2 feet above flood stage, expected to reach4 feet above flood stage Tuesday morning. High water closed someroads around Kansas City, Mo.   Strong southerly winds followed the thunderstorms in southernIowa and extreme northern Missouri. Wind gusts reached 58 miles anhour at Ottumwa, Iowa, and 47 miles an hour at Spickard, Mo.   Heavy rain also fell in parts of Minnesota and Wisconsin asthunderstorms moved across the area.   Thunderstorms were scattered across coastal parts of the Gulf andSouth Atlantic states, including the Florida Peninsula.Apalachicola, Fla., got 1{ inches of rain in two hours Mondayafternoon.   Skies were sunny on Labor Day across most of the Western half ofthe nation. Skies were partly cloudy or clear over inland sectionsof the Gulf Coast states, the Tennessee and Ohio valleys, theAppalachians and the Middle and North Atlantic coast states.   Hurricane Gabrielle, with highest sustained winds of 125 mph,continued to move toward the west northwest over the open Atlantic.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 106 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.The low in the Lower 48 states on Labor Day morning was 19 degreesat Jackson, Wyo.   The national forecast for Tuesday called for showers andthunderstorms from Florida and southern Georgia to the central GulfCoast; scattered showers and thunderstorms from the lower GreatLakes region across the lower Ohio and middle Mississippi valleys toparts of Kansas, Oklahoma and the Texas Panhandle; widely scatteredthunderstorms in the mountains of Arizona; and scattered showersfrom western Montana to Washington state.   High temperatures will be in the 70s from North Carolina to NewEngland, and from northern Michigan to Minnesota; in the 60s and 70sfrom the northern Rockies to the Pacific Northwest and along theCalifornia coast; 100 degrees in parts of Texas, and between 100 and110 degrees in the desert Southwest. Elsewhere, highs will be in the80s and 90s.</TEXT></DOC>